<html><head></head><body><b>Georg Simon Ohm (1787–1854)</b><br/>
German physicist. He formulated and justified theoretically the law that governs the relationship between the current that flows through a conductor and the applied voltage (known nowadays as Ohm’s Law). Ohm’s Law is one <br/>of the oldest and most important laws concerning electric current. It was devised in 1827. Ohm also dealt with acoustics. The unit of electrical resistance (the ohm) is named after him.</body></html>